    "Narration:"
    "You come back into the room like a wave coming over a wall—hard, energized, and carrying fragments. The legal pads, the printed trust drafts, the Beacon's logo on a glossy brochure: they scatter across a folding"
    "table like flotsam. Someone left a kettle half-burned on the counter; the smell of scorched tea undercuts the ozone tang of monitors."
    "Noah Reyes is there, sleeves rolled, jaw tight. Mayor Rosa hovers between paperwork and the window, hands folded so tightly her knuckles whiten. Lila Park stands three steps away from the projector, immaculate and glinting under"
    "lab light, as if she were a polished instrument the town must learn to play. Marta Chen and Eli Duarte have taken positions near the back—Marta Chen with her arms folded, Eli Duarte with a rag"
    "in his hand like a tool and a shield."
    "You can feel the room shrinking: urgency and accusation compressing air. Every ping from the Beacon is a reminder—this is not theoretical anymore. The sea is watching, and Marabel is answering with breath held."
    show asha_moreno at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_moreno "We pushed for guarantees. Resident seats. Transparency clauses.' 'What you offered at the table—Lila—wasn't a bridge. It was a leash."
    show lila_park at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lila_park "That's not fair, Asha.' 'We secured funding. We implemented sensors faster than anyone thought possible. The town asked for protection. We provided it."

    asha_moreno "You provided protection—and control. The plaques on the Promenade read like contracts. The market's stalls are emptying because rent packages changed overnight. People who can't afford to stay are taking buyouts. You engineered speed, Lila, but you engineered displacement too."

    lila_park "We designed options. Buyouts are capped—"

    asha_moreno "Options for whom? For people with savings? For a family who lost a boat and doesn't have a choice? You keep using words—'options', 'capped', 'managed'—but their houses were their histories."
    show noah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "Asha. We need to be strategic. Lila brought resources. We negotiated seat representation—"

    asha_moreno "Negotiated seats while signing away the shore,' 'Noah, how many concessions did you let slide in the legal drafts? You were always good at reading rooms—did you read this room as 'necessary compromise' or 'accepting a wound'?"

    noah_reyes "I read it as bruised people who needed roofs tonight. If I hadn't softened, half the council would have stalled and we'd have nothing. We would've had pilot data at best and more broken roofs by the morning."

    asha_moreno "So we trade names on plaques for roofs? We trade memory and the boatyard and mom-and-pop stalls for corporate PR? That's not the bargain I came back to Marabel to make."
    hide asha_moreno
    show mayor_rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_rosa_alvarez "This isn't simple. The budget buckets are real, Asha. People are frightened. Some accepted buyouts because they want their grandchildren to go to school without worrying which storm will take the foundation. We didn't force them."
    hide lila_park
    show marta_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_chen "And some of us are trying to keep things alive with raised beds and neighborhood watches.' 'We fought for community access to the sensors. We got it in writing—sort of. But what good is a written promise when your bank changes hands?"
    hide noah_reyes
    show eli_duarte at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_duarte "There are families packing tonight. My cousin Miriam took the offer. She says she can stop worrying about the leak under her son's mattress. I don't blame her. But the old boatshop? It's half-empty. You can smell tar and absence on that street now."
    "Narration:"
    "Words become flint. The lab is a furnace of accusation. Your hands shake when you pick up the compass; metal bites skin. Your chest is raw, like a hull scraped along rock. The pings from the Beacon sound too bright—reminders of something the town ceded for immediate safety."
    hide mayor_rosa_alvarez
    show noah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "We didn't give away everything. The trust has resident oversight—two seats on the board. We got clauses about data access and a cap on buyouts. It's not perfect, but it's something to hold—"
    hide marta_chen
    show asha_moreno at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_moreno "Two seats?' 'Two seats in a board with six corporate appointees. That's not oversight, Noah—that's a gesture. The legal language says there's a 'capped buyout' under 'extreme need.' Who defines 'extreme'? Who decides when families like my neighbor Santos walk away because his mosquito-netting business can't pay the new lease?"

    noah_reyes "I fought for definitions. I fought for timelines. I read through every clause until my eyes burned. We didn't give up on governance—we changed the structure so Marabel can function while we fight for more control from the inside."

    asha_moreno "From the inside we become inefficient guardians. From the outside we are preserved relics. Which would you rather leave to your kids, Noah? A functioning town without what made it 'us', or a messy, dangerous town that still bears the names and songs of its people?"

    noah_reyes "I don't want to lose what made it us either. I can't—' 'I thought keeping more people in their houses was the right path. I thought if I softened, I could buy time—time to build protections the community could control."

    asha_moreno "Buy time for what? For lawyers to rearrange terms? For developers to stage relief concerts and call it 'community building'?"
    hide eli_duarte
    show lila_park at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lila_park "Asha. This is getting personal. We are dealing with existential risks. We cannot wait indefinitely for pilot projects while houses fall and people drown. We have a model that works. We have partners ready to scale this. If Marabel wants to be a model, we can save thousands—"

    asha_moreno "Not if saving thousands means stealing the shore from the few hundred who built it. You do not 'save' a town by auctioning its memory."

    menu:
        "Tap your thumb across the compass, grounding yourself":
            "You feel the cold brass dent the pad of your thumb; it steadies you enough to ask another hard question."
        "Pull out your ledger and flip to the page with the signatures":
            "The ink smears where rain once fell; names look smaller when you read them under fluorescent light. You remember whose handwriting is missing."

