    "Narration:"
    "You walk the boardwalk because you have to see it with your own eyes. The plaques are there—small, square, impossible to ignore. 'In partnership with —' they begin; then corporate names curl in brushed metal. Between"
    "them, there is a spray of graffiti that someone scrawled at midnight: SAVE OUR DOCKS. The scrawl looks like a child's handwriting, and your throat tightens."
    "Your feet know the boards by memory. They remember the weight of your father's boots, the salt that used to live in seams of old rope. Tonight, those memories feel like contraband—too personal, not fundable."
    show asha_moreno at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_moreno "They made a monument to what they paid to keep."
    show eli_duarte at right:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_duarte "I fixed the best planks of the Promenade before they started the upgrades. They promised they'd keep the wood. They kept the boards, not the stories."
    show marta_chen at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_chen "We planted the first raised beds here. Every tomato plant had a name. A week ago Madame Lo's stall was full. Tonight the racks hang empty."
    "Narration:"
    "You stop by a place where, years ago, your father used to tether his skiff. The rotting rope is still looped around the post, frayed and honest. Your compass is heavy in your pocket; you take"
    "it out and hold it to the moonlight. It points, as it always does, indifferent to contracts and plaques."
    hide asha_moreno
    show noah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "I told them the truth—after the vote. I said what you wanted me to say. I remember your words when they named their clauses.' (He swallows, the sound wet.) 'Even then, I left things unsaid because I thought they'd listen later."
    hide eli_duarte
    show asha_moreno at right:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_moreno "Some things can't be listened into existence, Noah. Some losses are immediate."

    noah_reyes "I know I failed where you needed me to be hard. I am sorry. I thought I was protecting us in the only way I knew how."

    asha_moreno "I know. I don't know if that's enough."

    noah_reyes "If the town keeps most of its houses, if the marsh restoration takes root—if people can stay—"

    asha_moreno "Some will have left. Names will be missing at the market. The boatyard will feel smaller. The Promenade will have plaques where faces used to be. For many, that's not keeping the town. It's preserving a picture."

    noah_reyes "Then we grieve,' he says. 'Together? Separately? I don't know. But—' (He searches for softness.) 'I want you in that grieving, Asha. I don't want to be the reason you walk away."

    asha_moreno "I don't either. But I can't promise how I'll bear it. I can't promise that staying won't mean I've traded pieces of myself."

    noah_reyes "Then tell me what you need."

    asha_moreno "I need honesty,' 'Straight lines. No more gentle wording to keep rooms comfortable. If you can't do that—if you won't do the hard thing—say so. Don't hide behind compromise."

    noah_reyes "I will be honest, even when it hurts."
    "Narration:"
    "The promise is thin. It trembles between you like a net in wind. The Promenade air tastes like iron and old coffee. The plaques gleam with their newness. A gull cries and the note is a small, cruel punctuation."

    menu:
        "Trace the frayed rope where your father's skiff used to be":
            "The rope is rough and honest beneath your fingertips. You remember your father cursing at storms and laughing anyway. The memory is both comfort and a wound."
        "Turn and face Noah, and speak the hardest sentence":
            "You take a breath and say, 'If this is the price, I still choose the town—we will pay it, but I will not pretend it won't cost us.' The words land like stones between you."

